            "content": "# SQS Consumer Backend — Design Spec\n\n## Overview\n\nAdd an SQS consumer backend to the `shove` crate with full parity to the RabbitMQ consumer. This is the second phase of the SNS+SQS backend — consuming messages from SQS queues that are subscribed to SNS topics. Includes consumer groups and autoscaling.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Module Structure\n\nExtends the existing `src/backends/sns/` module:\n\n```\nsrc/backends/sns/\n├── mod.rs              # updated re-exports\n├── client.rs           # SnsClient (existing)\n├── publisher.rs        # SnsPublisher (existing, modified for shard attribute)\n├── topology.rs         # SnsTopologyDeclarer (existing, extended for SQS)\n├── consumer.rs         # SqsConsumer (implements Consumer)\n├── router.rs           # Outcome routing (delete, visibility change, DLQ)\n├── consumer_group.rs   # SqsConsumerGroup\n├── registry.rs         # SqsConsumerGroupRegistry\n└── autoscaler.rs       # SqsAutoscaler (uses GetQueueAttributes)\n```\n\n---\n\n## 2. Dependencies\n\nUpdate `sns` feature and add `aws-sdk-sqs`:\n\n```toml\nsns = [\"dep:aws-config\", \"dep:aws-sdk-sns\", \"dep:aws-sdk-sqs\"]\n```\n\nAdd `aws-sdk-sqs` as a regular optional dependency (no longer just dev-dep):\n\n```toml\naws-sdk-sqs = { version = \"1\", optional = true }\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3. SnsClient Extension\n\nAdd SQS client accessor to existing `SnsClient`:\n\n```rust\nimpl SnsClient {\n    // Existing: inner() -> &aws_sdk_sns::Client\n    pub(crate) fn sqs(&self) -> &aws_sdk_sqs::Client;\n}\n```\n\nThe SQS client is built from the same AWS config as SNS (same region, endpoint, credentials). Created lazily or eagerly during `SnsClient::new()`.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Topology Declarer Extension\n\n`SnsTopologyDeclarer` gains SQS queue creation for the consumer side.\n\n### Unsequenced Topics\n\n1. Create SNS standard topic (existing)\n2. Create SQS main queue with redrive policy pointing to DLQ\n3. Create SQS DLQ (if topology has `.dlq()`)\n4. Subscribe SQS main queue to SNS topic\n5. Set SQS queue policy to allow SNS delivery\n6. Register queue URL in a new `QueueRegistry`\n\n### Sequenced Topics\n\n1. Create SNS FIFO topic (existing)\n2. For each shard (0..routing_shards):\n   - Create SQS FIFO queue `{queue}-seq-{i}.fifo`\n   - Subscribe to SNS FIFO topic with filter policy: `{ \"shard\": [\"{i}\"] }`\n   - Set queue policy for SNS delivery\n   - Configure redrive policy to DLQ\n3. Create SQS DLQ (FIFO: `{queue}-dlq.fifo`, standard if unsequenced)\n4. Register all queue URLs in `QueueRegistry`\n\n### Publisher Modification (Sequenced)\n\nThe `SnsPublisher` must add a `shard` message attribute for sequenced topics:\n\n```rust\n// In publish for sequenced topics:\nlet shard = hash(sequence_key) % routing_shards;\nreq = req.message_attributes(\"shard\", MessageAttributeValue::builder()\n    .data_type(\"String\")\n    .string_value(shard.to_string())\n    .build()?);\n```\n\nThis enables SNS subscription filter policies to route messages to the correct shard queue.\n\n### QueueRegistry\n\n```rust\npub struct QueueRegistry {\n    urls: RwLock<HashMap<String, String>>,  // queue_name -> SQS queue URL\n}\n```\n\nShared between topology declarer and consumer via `Arc`.\n\n---\n\n## 5. SqsConsumer\n\nImplements the `Consumer` trait.\n\n### Structure\n\n```rust\npub struct SqsConsumer {\n    client: SnsClient,\n    queue_registry: Arc<QueueRegistry>,\n}\n```\n\n### Message Polling\n\nSQS uses long-polling via `ReceiveMessage`:\n- `WaitTimeSeconds: 20` (max long-poll, reduces API calls)\n- `MaxNumberOfMessages: min(10, prefetch_count)` (SQS max is 10 per call)\n- `MessageAttributeNames: [\"All\"]` to receive custom attributes\n- `AttributeNames: [\"All\"]` to receive system attributes (ApproximateReceiveCount)\n\n### Outcome Routing\n\n- **Ack**: `DeleteMessage` — remove from queue\n- **Retry**: `ChangeMessageVisibility` with timeout from `hold_queues[min(retry_count, len-1)].delay()`. If no hold queues, set visibility to 0 (immediate redelivery). Max visibility timeout is 12 hours.\n- **Reject**: `DeleteMessage` from main queue. SQS native redrive handles DLQ routing based on receive count (`maxReceiveCount` in redrive policy maps to `max_retries`).\n- **Defer**: `ChangeMessageVisibility` with timeout from `hold_queues[0].delay()`. Does not count against retries (SQS receive count stays the same — the message is the same receipt).\n\n### Retry Counting\n\nUse SQS native `ApproximateReceiveCount` attribute as retry count. This aligns with the native redrive policy (choice #2A). The `max_retries` from `ConsumerOptions` is set as `maxReceiveCount` in the SQS redrive policy during topology declaration.\n\n### Sequential Consumption (`run`)\n\nDelegates to `run_concurrent` with `prefetch_count = 1`, same as RabbitMQ.\n\n### Concurrent Consumption (`run_concurrent`)\n\n1. Poll SQS in batches (up to 10)\n2. Dispatch handler tasks concurrently\n3. Track in-flight messages in `VecDeque<PendingMessage>`\n4. Drain completed from front (in-order, same as RabbitMQ)\n5. Delete/route completed messages\n6. Respect shutdown token\n\nUnlike RabbitMQ, SQS doesn't push — we must poll. The loop:\n```\nloop {\n    drain_completed()\n    if can_accept_more && !shutdown {\n        poll SQS (up to min(10, available_slots))\n        for each message: spawn handler, push to in_flight\n    }\n    if shutdown { drain all in_flight, return }\n}\n```\n\n### Sequenced Consumption (`run_sequenced`)\n\nSpawn N shard consumers (one per `{queue}-seq-{i}.fifo`). Each shard consumer uses the per-key state machine identical to RabbitMQ:\n- `KeyState::InFlight` / `KeyState::AwaitingRetry`\n- Local buffering in `pending_deliveries: HashMap<String, VecDeque<SqsMessage>>`\n- `poisoned_keys: HashSet<String>` for FailAll\n- MessageGroupId from SQS message attributes maps to sequence key\n\n### DLQ Consumption (`run_dlq`)\n\nPoll the DLQ queue, deserialize, call `handler.handle_dead()`, always delete after.\n\n### Metadata Extraction\n\n```rust\n// SQS message -> MessageMetadata\nMessageMetadata {\n    retry_count: msg.attributes[\"ApproximateReceiveCount\"].parse() - 1,\n    delivery_id: msg.message_id,\n    redelivered: retry_count > 0,\n    headers: msg.message_attributes (string values),\n}\n\n// DLQ message -> DeadMessageMetadata\nDeadMessageMetadata {\n    message: MessageMetadata { ... },\n    reason: Some(\"max_receives_exceeded\"),\n    original_queue: Some(source_queue_name),\n    death_count: receive_count,\n}\n```\n\n### Reconnection / Error Handling\n\nSame pattern as RabbitMQ: wrap consumer loop with `run_with_reconnect`. On SQS errors (network, throttling), wait `RECONNECT_DELAY` (5s) and retry.\n\n### Header Preservation\n\nSQS message attributes persist across visibility timeout changes (the message keeps its attributes). Headers are preserved automatically. On Retry/Defer, since we use `ChangeMessageVisibility` (not re-publish), all attributes survive.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Consumer Groups\n\n### SqsConsumerGroup\n\nMirrors `ConsumerGroup` from RabbitMQ:\n\n```rust\npub struct SqsConsumerGroup {\n    name: String,\n    queue: String,\n    config: ConsumerGroupConfig,\n    spawner: Arc<dyn Fn(ConsumerOptions) -> JoinHandle<()> + Send + Sync>,\n    consumers: Vec<(CancellationToken, Arc<AtomicBool>, JoinHandle<()>)>,\n    group_token: CancellationToken,\n}\n```\n\nSame API: `start()`, `scale_up()`, `scale_down()`, `shutdown()`.\n\n### SqsConsumerGroupRegistry\n\n```rust\npub struct SqsConsumerGroupRegistry {\n    groups: HashMap<String, SqsConsumerGroup>,\n    client: SnsClient,\n}\n```\n\nSame API: `register()`, `start_all()`, `shutdown_all()`.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Autoscaler\n\n### SqsQueueStatsProvider\n\nImplements `QueueStatsProvider` using SQS `GetQueueAttributes`:\n\n```rust\nimpl QueueStatsProvider for SqsQueueStatsProvider {\n    async fn get_queue_stats(&self, queue: &str) -> Result<QueueStats> {\n        // GetQueueAttributes with:\n        // - ApproximateNumberOfMessages (messages_ready)\n        // - ApproximateNumberOfMessagesNotVisible (messages_unacked)\n        // Uses queue_registry to resolve queue name -> URL\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThe existing `Autoscaler` struct and `AutoscalerConfig` are backend-agnostic (they take `impl QueueStatsProvider`). No new autoscaler struct needed — just provide `SqsQueueStatsProvider`.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Testing Strategy\n\n### Unit Tests\n\n- Outcome routing logic (which action for each outcome)\n- Retry count extraction from SQS attributes\n- Metadata extraction\n- Shard computation for sequenced topics\n- Batch polling logic\n- Queue URL registry\n\n### Integration Tests\n\nIn `tests/sns_sqs_integration.rs` using LocalStack:\n\n- **Publish and consume single message** (round-trip SNS → SQS → consumer)\n- **Concurrent consumption** with in-order processing verification\n- **Sequenced consumption** with per-key ordering verification\n- **Retry with visibility timeout** — verify message reappears after delay\n- **DLQ routing** — exceed max receives, verify in DLQ\n- **DLQ consumption** — consume from DLQ, verify handle_dead called\n- **Consumer groups** — register, start, verify messages processed\n- **Autoscaler** — verify scale-up/down based on queue depth\n- **Graceful shutdown** — verify in-flight messages completed\n\n---\n\n## 9. Public API Surface\n\nNew exports from `src/lib.rs` (extend existing `sns` module):\n\n```rust\n#[cfg(feature = \"sns\")]\npub mod sns {\n    // Existing\n    pub use crate::backends::sns::client::{SnsClient, SnsConfig};\n    pub use crate::backends::sns::publisher::SnsPublisher;\n    pub use crate::backends::sns::topology::{SnsTopologyDeclarer, TopicRegistry};\n    // New\n    pub use crate::backends::sns::consumer::SqsConsumer;\n    pub use crate::backends::sns::consumer_group::{SqsConsumerGroup};\n    pub use crate::backends::sns::registry::SqsConsumerGroupRegistry;\n    pub use crate::backends::sns::autoscaler::SqsQueueStatsProvider;\n    pub use crate::backends::sns::topology::QueueRegistry;\n}\n```\n",
